body:
Someone else had mounting issues because they were using `withRouter` [inside of their `render` method](https://github.com/ReactTraining/react-router/issues/4630#issuecomment-284715357), which would create a new component every render.

```js
class MyComponent extends Component {
  render() {
    // Don't do this
    const RouterThing = withRouter(Thing)
    return <RouterThing />
  }
}
```

I'm not sure if that is what you're running into, but it is the only reason. I can think of right now that would be causing the unmount.

Likewise from https://github.com/ReactTraining/react-router/commit/f90d7539452f3362aa5d4eb6e9c281838650e8d9 ;  the `router.match` is overridden by the parent `Route`.

Not perfect, but one workaround is to set `computedMatch` to something truthy so render is always called. Just, like, don't actually use that value within `render`  

(and add the hoistStatics/ref code back if you need that functionality)

```js
import React from 'react'
import { Route } from 'react-router-dom'

const alwaysRenderWithRouter = (Component) => {
  const C = (props) => {
    const { ...remainingProps } = props
    return (
      <Route computedMatch={{}} render={routeComponentProps => (
        <Component {...remainingProps} {...routeComponentProps} />
      )} />
    )
  }

  C.displayName = `alwaysRenderWithRoute(${Component.displayName || Component.name})`
  C.WrappedComponent = Component

  return C
}

export default alwaysRenderWithRouter

```
